SIMPLE: seam
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seam
<hw>Seam</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Saim</er>.]</ety> <def>Grease; tallow; lard.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au> <au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seam
<hw>Seam</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>seem</ets>, <ets>seam</ets>,
AS. <ets>se⟦aacute⟧m</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zoom</ets>, OHG.
<ets>soum</ets>, G. <ets>saum</ets>, LG. <ets>soom</ets>, Icel.
<ets>saumr</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>s⟦oum⟧m</ets>, and E. <ets>sew</ets>.
⟦root⟧ 156. See <er>Sew</er> to fasten with thread.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The fold or line formed by sewing together two pieces of cloth or
leather.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a line of junction; a joint; a suture, as on
a ship, a floor, or other structure; the line of union, or joint, of two
boards, planks, metal plates, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Precepts should be so finely wrought together . . . that no coarse
<qex>seam</qex> may discover where they join.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geol. & Mining)</fld> <def>A thin layer or stratum;
a narrow vein between two thicker strata; <as>as, a <ex>seam</ex> of
coal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A line or depression left by a cut or wound; a scar;
a cicatrix.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Seam blast</b></col>, <cd>a blast made by putting the
powder into seams or cracks of rocks.</cd> -- <col><b>Seam
lace</b></col>, <cd>a lace used by carriage makers to cover seams and
edges; -- called also <altname>seaming lace</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Seam presser</b></col>. <fld>(Agric.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A
heavy roller to press down newly plowed furrows</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A
tailor's sadiron for pressing seams.</cd> <au>Knight.</au> --
<col><b>Seam set</b></col>, <cd>a set for flattering the seams of metal
sheets, leather work, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Seam
<hw>Seam</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Seamed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Seaming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form a seam upon
or of; to join by sewing together; to unite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mark with something resembling a seam; to line;
to scar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Seamed</qex> o'er with wounds which his own saber gave.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make the appearance of a seam in, as in knitting
a stocking; hence, to knit with a certain stitch, like that in such
knitting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Seam
<hw>Seam</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become ridgy; to crack
open.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Later their lips began to parch and <qex>seam</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>L. Wallace.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Seam
<hw>Seam</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>se⟦aacute⟧m</ets>, LL.
<ets>sauma</ets>, L. <ets>sagma</ets> a packsaddle, fr. Gr. <?/. See
<er>Sumpter</er>.]</ety> <def>A denomination of weight or measure.</def>
Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The quantity of eight bushels of
grain.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>seam</xex> of oats.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>P.
Plowman.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The quantity of 120 pounds of
glass.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sea-maid</ent>⟦br⟧
